iousness and sensibility of readers, listeners, and viewers by way of dynamic encounters with works of art. Aesthetic Dilemmas thereby corrects a long-standing, flawed characterization of Hofmannsthal’s work as escapist and demonstrates how his place in the Modernist movement has been misunderstood in most scholarship. The book is in dialogue with a broad range of critical voices and treats a variety of themes, from aestheticism to money, interpersonal relationships, suffering, poverty, labour, futurity, legacy, and hope. Translating numerous passages into English for the first time, Aesthetic Dilemmas gives English-speaking readers the chance to evaluate Hofmannsthal’s literary merit and his contributions to the enduring conversation about art’s relation to ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  a672 Nacht.  aAndreas.  aAugenblicke.  aAustrian.  aBriefe.  aElektra.  aEuropean.  aFrau.  aFriedrich.  aGeorg Simmel.  aGerman.  aGreece.  aGriechenland.  aLetters.  aMan.  aMarchen.  aMartin Buber.  aMoments.  aNietzsche.  aNight 672.  aRainer Maria Rilke.  aReturned.  aRichard Strauss.  aSchatten.  aShadow.  aStefan George.  aTale.  aVienna.  aViennese.  aVincent van Gogh.  aWalter Pater.  aWoman.  aZuruckgekehrten.  acentury.  acriticism.  adecadence.  adialogical.  aekphrasis.  aethics.  afin de siecle.  aimpressionism.  alabor.  aliterature.  amusic.  apainting.  aphilosophy.  asculpture.  aturn.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978